<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="ic4-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>IC-4 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems.  Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <page>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Given <m>\int_0^4\int_{y/2}^{y/2+1} x-\frac{y}{2}dxdy</m> 
            and the transformation <m>T:(u,v)\rightarrow(x,y)</m> by 
            <m>T(u,v)=(u+v,2v)</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Sketch the region of integration in the <m>xy</m>-plane.</p></statement>
            <answer><image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-ic5a-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <coordinates bbox="(-1,-1,4,5)">
                        <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                        <path start="(0,0)" stroke="blue" fill="lightgray">
                        <lineto point="(1,0)"/>
                        <lineto point="(3,4)"/>
                        <lineto point="(2,4)"/>
                        <lineto point="(0,0)"/>
                        </path>
                        <label anchor="(1.5,2)"><m>R</m></label>
                    </coordinates>
                    <annotations>
                        text="R is the parallelogram with vertices (0,0), (1,0), (3,4) and (2,4).">
                        <annotation ref="path"
                                    text="R is the parallelogram with vertices (0,0), (1,0), (3,4) and (2,4)."/>
                    </annotations>
                    </diagram>
                </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Sketch the region of integration in the <m>uv</m>-plane.</p></statement>
            <answer><image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-ic5b-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <coordinates bbox="(-1,-1,2,3)">
                        <grid-axes xlabel="u" ylabel="v"/>
                        <path start="(0,0)" stroke="blue" fill="lightgray">
                        <lineto point="(1,0)"/>
                        <lineto point="(1,2)"/>
                        <lineto point="(0,2)"/>
                        <lineto point="(0,0)"/>
                        </path>
                        <label anchor="(0.5,1)"><m>R</m></label>
                    </coordinates>
                    <annotations>
                        text="R is the rectangle with vertices (0,0), (1,0), (1,2) and (0,2).">
                        <annotation ref="path"
                                    text="R is the rectangle with vertices (0,0), (1,0), (1,2) and (0,2)."/>
                    </annotations>
                    </diagram>
                </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the Jacobian of the transformation.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the Jacobian, compute the partial derivatives of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with respect to <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>J(u,v) = 2</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p><m>J(u,v) = \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial x}{\partial u} &amp; \frac{\partial x}{\partial v} \\ \frac{\partial y}{\partial u} &amp; \frac{\partial y}{\partial v} \end{vmatrix}</m></p>
                <p><m>J(u,v) = \begin{vmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 2 \end{vmatrix}</m></p>
                <p><m>J(u,v)=(1)(2)-(1)(0)</m></p>
                <p><m>J(u,v) = 2</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Use the transformation and the Jacobian to evaluate the integral.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Substitute the transformation into the integral and multiply by the Jacobian.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>\int_0^4\int_{y/2}^{y/2+1} x-\frac{y}{2}dxdy = 2</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>Using the region in the <m>uv</m>-plane, we have:</p>
                <p><m>\int_0^4\int_{y/2}^{y/2+1} x-\frac{y}{2}dxdy =\int_0^2\int_0^1 (u+v)-v dv du</m></p>
                <p><m>= \int_0^2\int_0^1 u dv du</m></p>
                <p><m>= \int_0^2 u du</m></p>
                <p><m>= \left[\frac{u^2}{2}\right]_0^2</m></p>
                <p><m>= 2</m></p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Given <m>x=e^{2u-v}</m> and <m>y=e^{u+v}</m>.</p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the Jacobian, <m>J(u,v)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the Jacobian, compute the partial derivatives of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> with respect to <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>J(u,v) = 3e^{3u}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the Jacobian, we compute the partial derivatives:</p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial x}{\partial u} = 2e^{2u-v}, \quad \frac{\partial x}{\partial v} = -e^{2u-v}</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial y}{\partial u} = e^{u+v}, \quad \frac{\partial y}{\partial v} = e^{u+v}</m></p>
                <p>Thus,</p>
                <p><m>J(u,v) = \begin{vmatrix} 2e^{2u-v} &amp; -e^{2u-v} \\ e^{u+v} &amp; e^{u+v} \end{vmatrix}</m></p>
                <p><m>= 2e^{2u-v} \cdot e^{u+v} - (-e^{2u-v}) \cdot e^{u+v}</m></p>
                <p><m>= 2e^{3u} + e^{3u}</m></p>
                <p><m>= 3e^{3u}</m></p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Use the above Jacobian to evaluate <m>\iint_R (xy) dA</m> 
                where <m>R</m> is the triangle defined by the equations <m>y=x, x=1</m>, 
                and <m>y=2x</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p></p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \frac{7e^{6}}{24}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>First we find the region in the <m>uv</m>-plane that corresponds to <m>R</m>.</p>
            <image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-ic5c-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <coordinates bbox="(-1,-1,2,3)">
                        <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                        <path start="(0,0)" stroke="blue" fill="lightgray">
                        <lineto point="(1,1)"/>
                        <lineto point="(1,2)"/>
                        <lineto point="(0,0)"/>
                        </path>
                        <label anchor="(0.75,1)"><m>R</m></label>
                    </coordinates>
                    <annotations>
                        text="R is the rectangle with vertices (0,0), (1,1), and (1,2).">
                        <annotation ref="path"
                                    text="R is the rectangle with vertices (0,0), (1,1), and (1,2)."/>
                    </annotations>
                    </diagram>
                </prefigure>
            </image>
            <p>Next we find the region in the <m>uv</m>-plane that corresponds to <m>R</m>.</p>
            <image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-ic5d-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <coordinates bbox="(-1,-1,3,5)">
                        <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                        <path start="(1,2-ln(2))" stroke="blue" fill="lightgray">
                        <lineto point="(1,2)"/>
                        <lineto point="(2,4)"/>
                        <lineto point="(2,4-ln(2))"/>
                        <lineto point="(1,2-ln(2))"/>
                        </path>
                        <label anchor="(1.5,2.75)"><m>R</m></label>
                    </coordinates>
                    <annotations>
                        text="R is a parallelogram.">
                        <annotation ref="graph-f"
                                    text="R is a parallelogram."/>
                    </annotations>
                    </diagram>
                </prefigure>
            </image>
            <p>Now we can evaluate the integral:</p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \iint_R e^{3u} du dv</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \int_{1}^{2} \int_{2-ln(2)}^{2} e^{3u} du dv</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \int_{1}^{2} \left[\frac{e^{3u}}{3}\right]_{2-ln(2)}^{2} dv</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \int_{1}^{2} \frac{e^{6}-e^{6-3ln(2)}}{3} dv</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \int_{1}^{2} \frac{e^{6}-\frac{e^{6}}{8}}{3} dv</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \int_{1}^{2} \frac{7e^{6}}{24} dv</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \left[\frac{7e^{6}}{24}v\right]_{1}^{2}</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R (xy) dA = \frac{7e^{6}}{24}</m></p>
        </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  </worksheet>